article:
A 'uniform polytope' of dimension three or higher is a vertex-transitive
polytope bounded by uniform facets. The uniform polytopes in two dimensions are
the regular polygons.

This is a generalization of the older category of '''semiregular''' polytopes,
but also includes the regular polytopes. Further, nonconvex regular faces and
vertex figures (star polygons) are allowed, which greatly expand the possible
solutions. A strict definition requires uniform polytopes to be finite, while a
more expansive definition allows uniform tessellations (tilings and honeycombs)
of Euclidean and hyperbolic space to be considered polytopes as well.
